Cases 13CF432, 13CF456 & 14CF32 called together at 1:23 pm
Defendant Colleen H Willis in court with Attorney John V. Rhiel. ADA Theresa Ann Beck appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

14CF32: Court examines the Defendant as to rights, understanding & intent.  
Ms. Willis waives her right to Preliminary Hearing; the Court accepts this waiver and binds her over for Arraignment.
State files information; Arraignment:--service of Information admitted, reading waived

Constitutional rights reviewed; maximum penalties recited; plea of "Guilty" entered on Counts #1 & #2; factual basis stipulated; victim rights compliance verified; Court finds the plea has been entered freely, voluntarily, intelligently and accepts the plea, finds the Defendant  guilty, and orders JOC entered.

As to all Cases: Sentencing Arguments by ADA Beck
off-record: 1:57 - 1:59 pm (for Atty Rhiel to discuss Court's proposal re: probation)
Sentencing Arguments by Atty Rhiel

On Count #1-13CF432, the Court withholds sentence and places Ms. Willis on probation for 3 years, concurrent to 13CF456 & 14CF32, with conditions:
-The Court gives 1 days credit for time already served-14CF432

On Count #1-13CF456, the Court sentences Ms. Willis to 4 years, with an Initial Term of Confinement in Prison of 2 years and the maximum time to serve on Extended Supervision of 2 years.  This sentence is to commence forthwith & concurrent to 14CF32 & 13CF432

On Counts #1 & #2-14CF32, the Court sentences Ms. Willis to 4 years, with an Initial Term of Confinement in Prison of 2 years and the maximum time to serve on Extended Supervision of 2 years, each count, concurrent. This sentence is to commence concurrent to 13CF456 & 13CF432

The Court finds that the Defendant is eligible for the Substance Abuse Program-14CF32 & 13CF456
The Court finds that the Defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program (Boot Camp)-14CF32 & 13CF456

The Court gives 1 day credit for time already served.
-13CF456
The Court gives 53 days credit for time already served.-14CF32

Case called at 1:26 pm
Defendant Colleen H Willis in custody, via video from the Jefferson County Jail with Attorney Elizabeth Svehlek from the Jefferson County Public Defenders Office. Public Service Special Prosecutor Melanie Flint appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Court reviews that todays hearing is in regards to the SCRAM install date if bond is not posted.
Court amends the bond to include language that:
--Should Ms. Willis be released she is to report to the Clerk of Court for determination of when the next SCRAM install date is and to appear at the next SCRAM install date.

recess: 1:29 pm
Clerks note advising def is still in custody
Conflict review worksheet
Scheduling notice

Case called at 2:21 pm
Defendant Colleen H Willis in custody, via video from the Jefferson County Jail with Attorney Elizabeth Svehlek from the Jefferson County Public Defenders Office. DA Susan Happ appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Upon stipulation, the Court finds the video connection to be sight and sound sufficient. 
Attorney Svehlek informs the Court that the defendant qualifies for SPD representation.
Court reviews conflict review worksheet that was emailed to the Court by the Court's Judicial Assistant. Court finds no conflict.
Service of Complaint admitted; reading waived; charges and maximum penalties recited
Court has reviewed the criminal complaint and finds that it states probable cause to support Count #1 & #2
Bail/Bond recommendations presented by counsel.

Court requires $150.00 CASH bond, with conditions: 
-No possession or consumption of alcohol 
-No presence in bars, taverns or liquor stores 
-No presence at Gaugert's Mobil Mart in Sullivan WI
-Not to drive any motor vehicle under any circumstances
-Defendant to report and comply with SCRAM alcohol monitoring program as administered by Wisconsin Community Services.  Defendant to comply with all SCRAM Program conditions of participation including payment of program costs and fees. Defendant to report for SCRAM installation in Room 230 of the Jefferson County Courthouse on 1/20/14 at 1:30 pm.

Preliminary Hearing time limits waived by both parties.
Attorney Svehlek requests that the Preliminary Hearing for this case be set at the same date and time as the sentencing in the defendant's other cases.

Recess: 2:32 pm
